  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Alvarez Homer Powers Houston Comeback Past Minnesota",
    "subheadline": "Houston Astros rallies past Minnesota Twins, MIN 4, HOU 6.",
    "lead_angle": "Yordan Alvarez erased a three-run Minnesota lead with a single swing, launching a Joe Ryan offering into the right-field seats to power the Houston Astros to a 6-4 victory. The home run was the centerpiece of a chaotic six-run fourth inning that turned the game on its head at Daikin Park. The rally flipped a contest the Minnesota Twins had controlled from the outset. Mike Burrows gets the win for the Astros in relief, while Ryan takes the loss, undone by that one disastrous frame.\n\nMinnesota looked sharp early, pushing across three runs in the first inning on a two-run knock from Ryan Kreidler and an error. For three innings, Ryan silenced the Houston bats, navigating the lineup with ease and protecting the lead. But the game unraveled for him in the fourth. The Astros sent ten men to the plate, stringing together hits and walks to load the bases before Alvarez delivered the punishing blow that gave Houston a lead it would not surrender.\n\nThe night belonged to Alvarez. He finished 3-for-4 with four runs batted in, personally out-producing the entire Twins offense. The win is a crucial one for an Astros team jockeying for playoff position, especially against a fellow contender. After Burrows steered the game into the ninth, Josh Hader came on to close the books, striking out two to earn the save and cement the comeback.",
    "reason": "A 3-run comeback is the day's best storyline — resilience over résumé."
  },
